In 
 Table 5, smallholder farmers’ experiences of climate change are presented. The majority of the farmers have experienced late onset and early cessation of rainfall in the district as reported by 82.8% and 89.2% of respondents, respectively. Previous studies have reported that smallholder famers in Ghana have observed early cessation and late onset of rainfall (
 Limantol et al., 2016; 
 Ndamani and Watanabe, 2015). 
 Chepkoech et al. (2018) and (
 Abid et al., 2015) reported similar findings in Kenya and Pakistan, respectively. The observed changes in climate have affected the predictability of rainfall by smallholder farmers, who require such information for their agricultural activities. A vast majority of the smallholder farmers (94.7%) have also experienced decrease in the duration of rainfall while about 82.5% of the farmers have observed an increase in rainfall intensity. Unpredictability of rainfall by smallholder farmers and decrease in rainfall duration have been reported in existing literature (
 Abid et al., 2015; 
 Chepkoech et al., 2018; 
 Fadina and Barjolle, 2018).
